body:
When enabled, the table optimization will generate code that creates a warning at compilation. This prevents the executable form being compiled with default arguments.

```Verilog
// DESCRIPTION: Verilator: Verilog Test module
//
// This file ONLY is placed under the Creative Commons Public Domain, for
// any use, without warranty, 2024.
// SPDX-License-Identifier: CC0-1.0

module test;

reg [2:0] foo;
real bar;

always @(foo) begin
  case (foo)
    3'd0:   bar = 0.0;
    3'd1:   bar = 1.0;
    3'd2:   bar = 2.0;
    3'd3:   bar = 3.0;
    3'd4:   bar = 4.0;
    3'd5:   bar = 5.0;
    3'd6:   bar = 6.0;
    3'd7:   bar = 7.0;
  endcase
end

initial begin
  foo = 0;
  bar = 0;
  #10 foo = 3'd6;

  $write("",bar); // Force bar to be used, avoid optimizing out
  $finish;
end


endmodule;
```
When compilating the Verilated code, i get the warning : `Vtest__ConstPool_0.cpp:12:2: error: narrowing conversion of ‘1.0e+0’ from ‘double’ to ‘long unsigned int’ [-Wnarrowing]` for every `real` value of the `case`.

This arises from the way the tables are stored in the const pools : if they are not a string, Verilator gives them the 64bit size equivalent `QData` (from the `real` size) but writes the `double` values. I think I have an acceptable fix.

To run the example, i use `verilator --cc --exe --build --timing --main -O3 test.v`

This bug was discovered in Verilator v5.022 and is still present on the git master.

I am using Pop!OS 22.04 LTS (based on Ubuntu 22.04).
